SourceData.SourceString: Distance from start of ribbon that the particle lies.
The lifetime of a particle in seconds.
Used to drive the Particle Random node in the Material Editor. Without this set, any Particle Randoms will get 0.0.
The position of the particle. This is its own type for LWC support.

Mass is factored into the Solver Calculations (Solve Forces and Solve Rotational Forces) where forces are converted into a final velocity. The more massive a particle, the more force is required to move it.
The age in seconds. Useful for tracking how long a particle's been present in the scene.
The age in seconds divided by lifetime in seconds. Useful for animation as the value is between 0 and 1.
The size of the sprite quad.
The velocity in cm/s of the particle.
Makes the surface of the sprite face towards a custom vector. Must be used with the SpriteRenderer's CustomFacingVector FacingMode option.
Imagine the texture having an arrow pointing up, this attribute makes the arrow point towards the alignment axis. Must be used with the SpriteRenderer's CustomAlignment Alignment option.
The 4-float vector used to send custom data to renderer.
Returns skinning dependant data for the pased MeshTriCoord in world space. All outputs are optional and you will incur zerp minimal cost if they are not connected.

Tags.string 'NodeComment':
Sample the skeletal mesh to have the particle spawn on it. 
Color is set by a user variable from the bot to match bots color. In his material and here we use a hue shift. 
Some curl noise and gravity gives us a nice simple effect.
